Most people in rural North America

260
0:11:10.26,000 --> 0:11:13,000
owned some land by 1900.

261
0:11:13.26,000 --> 0:11:15,000
Hardly anyone in South America did.

262
0:11:15.26,000 --> 0:11:18,000
That's another killer app.

263
0:11:18.26,000 --> 0:11:2,000
Modern medicine in the late 19th century

264
0:11:20.26,000 --> 0:11:22,000
began to make major breakthroughs

265
0:11:22.26,000 --> 0:11:24,000
against the infectious diseases that killed a lot of people.

266
0:11:24.26,000 --> 0:11:26,000
And this was another killer app --

267
0:11:26.26,000 --> 0:11:28,000
the very opposite of a killer,

268
0:11:28.26,000 --> 0:11:31,000
because it doubled, and then more than doubled, human life expectancy.

269
0:11:31.26,000 --> 0:11:33,000
It even did that

270
0:11:33.26,000 --> 0:11:35,000
in the European empires.

271
0:11:35.26,000 --> 0:11:37,000
Even in places like Senegal,

272
0:11:37.26,000 --> 0:11:39,000
beginning in the early 20th century,

273
0:11:39.26,000 --> 0:11:41,000
there were major breakthroughs in public health,

274
0:11:41.26,000 --> 0:11:43,000
and life expectancy began to rise.

275
0:11:43.26,000 --> 0:11:45,000
It doesn't rise any faster

276
0:11:45.26,000 --> 0:11:47,000
after these countries become independent.

277
0:11:47.26,000 --> 0:11:49,000
The empires weren't all bad.

278
0:11:49.26,000 --> 0:11:51,000
The consumer society is what you need

279
0:11:51.26,000 --> 0:11:54,000
for the Industrial Revolution to have a point.

280
0:11:54.26,000 --> 0:11:56,000
You need people to want to wear tons of clothes.

281
0:11:56.26,000 --> 0:11:58,000
You've all bought an article of clothing in the last month;

282
0:11:58.26,000 --> 0:12:,000
I guarantee it.

283
0:12:00.26,000 --> 0:12:02,000
That's the consumer society,

284
0:12:02.26,000 --> 0:12:04,000
and it propels economic growth

285
0:12:04.26,000 --> 0:12:07,000
more than even technological change itself.

286
0:12:07.26,000 --> 0:12:09,000
Japan was the first non-Western society

287
0:12:09.26,000 --> 0:12:11,000
to embrace it.

288
0:12:11.26,000 --> 0:12:13,000
The alternative,

289
0:12:13.26,000 --> 0:12:15,000
which was proposed by Mahatma Gandhi,

290
0:12:15.26,000 --> 0:12:18,000
was to institutionalize and make poverty permanent.

291
0:12:18.26,000 --> 0:12:2,000
Very few Indians today

292
0:12:20.26,000 --> 0:12:22,000
wish that India had gone down

293
0:12:22.26,000 --> 0:12:25,000
Mahatma Gandhi's road.

294
0:12:25.26,000 --> 0:12:27,000
Finally, the work ethic.

295
0:12:27.26,000 --> 0:12:3,000
Max Weber thought that was peculiarly Protestant.

296
0:12:30.26,000 --> 0:12:32,000
He was wrong.

297
0:12:32.26,000 --> 0:12:34,000
Any culture can get the work ethic

298
0:12:34.26,000 --> 0:12:36,000
if the institutions are there

299
0:12:36.26,000 --> 0:12:38,000
to create the incentive to work.

300
0:12:38.26,000 --> 0:12:4,000
We know this

301
0:12:40.26,000 --> 0:12:42,000
because today the work ethic

302
0:12:42.26,000 --> 0:12:45,000
is no longer a Protestant, Western phenomenon.

303
0:12:45.26,000 --> 0:12:48,000
In fact, the West has lost its work ethic.

304
0:12:48.26,000 --> 0:12:51,000
Today, the average Korean

305
0:12:51.26,000 --> 0:12:55,000
works a thousand hours more a year

306
0:12:55.26,000 --> 0:12:57,000
than the average German --

307
0:12:57.26,000 --> 0:12:59,000
a thousand.

308
0:12:59.26,000 --> 0:13:01,000
And this is part

309
0:13:01.26,000 --> 0:13:04,000
of a really extraordinary phenomenon,

310
0:13:04.26,000 --> 0:13:07,000
and that is the end of the Great Divergence.

311
0:13:07.26,000 --> 0:13:09,000
Who's got the work ethic now?

312
0:13:09.26,000 --> 0:13:12,000
Take a look at mathematical attainment

313
0:13:12.26,000 --> 0:13:14,000
by 15 year-olds.

314
0:13:14.26,000 --> 0:13:16,000
At the top of the international league table

315
0:13:16.26,000 --> 0:13:19,000
according to the latest PISA study,

316
0:13:19.26,000 --> 0:13:21,000
is the Shanghai district of China.

317
0:13:21.26,000 --> 0:13:23,000
The gap between Shanghai

318
0:13:23.26,000 --> 0:13:26,000
and the United Kingdom and the United States

319
0:13:26.26,000 --> 0:13:29,000
is as big as the gap between the U.K. and the U.S.

320
0:13:29.26,000 --> 0:13:32,000
and Albania and Tunisia.

321
0:13:32.26,000 --> 0:13:34,000
You probably assume

322
0:13:34.26,000 --> 0:13:36,000
that because the iPhone was designed in California

323
0:13:36.26,000 --> 0:13:38,000
but assembled in China

324
0:13:38.26,000 --> 0:13:41,000
that the West still leads in terms of technological innovation.

325
0:13:41.26,000 --> 0:13:43,000
You're wrong.

326
0:13:43.26,000 --> 0:13:45,000
In terms of patents,

327
0:13:45.26,000 --> 0:13:47,000
there's no question that the East is ahead.

328
0:13:47.26,000 --> 0:13:5,000
Not only has Japan been ahead for some time,

329
0:13:50.26,000 --> 0:13:53,000
South Korea has gone into third place,

330
0:13:53.26,000 --> 0:13:56,000
and China is just about to overtake Germany.

331
0:13:56.26,000 --> 0:13:58,000
Why?

332
0:13:58.26,000 --> 0:14:,000
Because the killer apps can be downloaded.

333
0:14:00.26,000 --> 0:14:02,000
It's open source.

334
0:14:02.26,000 --> 0:14:04,000
Any society can adopt these institutions,

335
0:14:04.26,000 --> 0:14:06,000
and when they do,

336
0:14:06.26,000 --> 0:14:1,000
they achieve what the West achieved after 1500 --

337
0:14:10.26,000 --> 0:14:12,000
only faster.

338
0:14:12.26,000 --> 0:14:14,000
This is the Great Reconvergence,

339
0:14:14.26,000 --> 0:14:18,000
and it's the biggest story of your lifetime.

340
0:14:18.26,000 --> 0:14:21,000
Because it's on your watch that this is happening.

341
0:14:21.26,000 --> 0:14:23,000
It's our generation

342
0:14:23.26,000 --> 0:14:25,000
that is witnessing the end of Western predominance.

343
0:14:25.26,000 --> 0:14:27,000
The average American used to be more than 20 times richer

344
0:14:27.26,000 --> 0:14:29,000
than the average Chinese.

345
0:14:29.26,000 --> 0:14:31,000
Now it's just five times,

346
0:14:31.26,000 --> 0:14:33,000
and soon it will be 2.5 times.

347
0:14:33.26,000 --> 0:14:36,000
So I want to end with three questions

348
0:14:36.26,000 --> 0:14:38,000
for the future billions,

349
0:14:38.26,000 --> 0:14:41,000
just ahead of 2016,

350
0:14:41.26,000 --> 0:14:43,000
when the United States will lose its place

351
0:14:43.26,000 --> 0:14:46,000
as number one economy to China.

352
0:14:46.26,000 --> 0:14:5,000
The first is, can you delete these apps,

353
0:14:50.26,000 --> 0:14:52,000
and are we in the process of doing so

354
0:14:52.26,000 --> 0:14:54,000
in the Western world?

355
0:14:54.26,000 --> 0:14:56,000
The second question is,

356
0:14:56.26,000 --> 0:15:,000
does the sequencing of the download matter?

357
0:15:00.26,000 --> 0:15:05,000
And could Africa get that sequencing wrong?

358
0:15:05.26,000 --> 0:15:07,000
One obvious implication of modern economic history

359
0:15:07.26,000 --> 0:15:1,000
is that it's quite hard to transition to democracy

360
0:15:10.26,000 --> 0:15:12,000
before you've established

361
0:15:12.26,000 --> 0:15:15,000
secure private property rights.

362
0:15:15.26,000 --> 0:15:18,000
Warning: that may not work.

363
0:15:18.26,000 --> 0:15:2,000
And third, can China do without

364
0:15:20.26,000 --> 0:15:22,000
killer app number three?

365
0:15:22.26,000 --> 0:15:26,000
That's the one that John Locke systematized

366
0:15:26.26,000 --> 0:15:3,000
when he said that freedom was rooted in private property rights

367
0:15:30.26,000 --> 0:15:32,000
and the protection of law.

368
0:15:32.26,000 --> 0:15:34,000
That's the basis

369
0:15:34.26,000 --> 0:15:36,000
for the Western model

370
0:15:36.26,000 --> 0:15:39,000
of representative government.

371
0:15:39.26,000 --> 0:15:41,000
Now this picture shows the demolition

372
0:15:41.26,000 --> 0:15:44,000
of the Chinese artist Ai Weiwei's studio

373
0:15:44.26,000 --> 0:15:46,000
in Shanghai earlier this year.

374
0:15:46.26,000 --> 0:15:48,000
He's now free again,

375
0:15:48.26,000 --> 0:15:5,000
having been detained, as you know, for some time.

376
0:15:50.26,000 --> 0:15:53,000
But I don't think his studio has been rebuilt.

377
0:15:55.26,000 --> 0:15:59,000
Winston Churchill once defined civilization

378
0:15:59.26,000 --> 0:16:03,000
in a lecture he gave in the fateful year of 1938.

379
0:16:03.26,000 --> 0:16:06,000
And I think these words really nail it:

380
0:16:06.26,000 --> 0:16:1,000
"It means a society based upon the opinion of civilians.

381
0:16:10.26,000 --> 0:16:13,000
It means that violence, the rule of warriors and despotic chiefs,

382
0:16:13.26,000 --> 0:16:16,000
the conditions of camps and warfare, of riot and tyranny,

383
0:16:16.26,000 --> 0:16:19,000
give place to parliaments where laws are made,

384
0:16:19.26,000 --> 0:16:21,000
and independent courts of justice

385
0:16:21.26,000 --> 0:16:24,000
in which over long periods those laws are maintained.

386
0:16:24.26,000 --> 0:16:26,000
That is civilization --

387
0:16:26.26,000 --> 0:16:28,000
and in its soil grow continually

388
0:16:28.26,000 --> 0:16:31,000
freedom, comfort and culture,"

389
0:16:31.26,000 --> 0:16:35,000
what all TEDsters care about most.

390
0:16:35.26,000 --> 0:16:38,000
"When civilization reigns in any country,

391
0:16:38.26,000 --> 0:16:41,000
a wider and less harassed life

392
0:16:41.26,000 --> 0:16:44,000
is afforded to the masses of the people."

393
0:16:44.26,000 --> 0:16:47,000
That's so true.

394
0:16:48.26,000 --> 0:16:51,000
I don't think the decline of Western civilization

395
0:16:51.26,000 --> 0:16:53,000
is inevitable,

396
0:16:53.26,000 --> 0:16:56,000
because I don't think history operates

397
0:16:56.26,000 --> 0:16:58,000
in this kind of life-cycle model,

398
0:16:58.26,000 --> 0:17:,000
beautifully illustrated by Thomas Cole's

399
0:17:00.26,000 --> 0:17:03,000
"Course of Empire" paintings.

400
0:17:03.26,000 --> 0:17:06,000
That's not the way history works.

401
0:17:06.26,000 --> 0:17:08,000
That's not the way the West rose,

402
0:17:08.26,000 --> 0:17:11,000
and I don't think it's the way the West will fall.

403
0:17:11.26,000 --> 0:17:14,000
The West may collapse very suddenly.

404
0:17:14.26,000 --> 0:17:17,000
Complex civilizations do that,

405
0:17:17.26,000 --> 0:17:19,000
because they operate, most of the time,

406
0:17:19.26,000 --> 0:17:21,000
on the edge of chaos.

407
0:17:21.26,000 --> 0:17:24,000
That's one of the most profound insights

408
0:17:24.26,000 --> 0:17:27,000
to come out of the historical study of complex institutions

409
0:17:27.26,000 --> 0:17:3,000
like civilizations.

410
0:17:30.26,000 --> 0:17:32,000
No, we may hang on,

411
0:17:32.26,000 --> 0:17:36,000
despite the huge burdens of debt that we've accumulated,

412
0:17:36.26,000 --> 0:17:39,000
despite the evidence that we've lost our work ethic

